Web scarping dynamic websites

Problems from the previous class

We tried:

  • scrape prices from “Search” page: a character vector of "-"s
  • scrape names, rating, and prices from “Explore” page: an empty character vector character(0)

In other words, both of them returned no content.

Under the hood

Static vs dynamic web-pages

Static approach:

  • The entire web-page (including all of its content and data) is generated on the server-side, and then fetched all at once by the client.

  • The client can get the next piece of data by loading a new page (e.g., the next page).

  • The page is static object, it does not interact with the server anymore.

Static vs dynamic web-pages

Dynamic approach:

  • The web-page (the structure) is again generated on the server side, but the data is loaded “on demand” as a response to user actions (by calling JavaScript).

  • The client can get the next piece of data by, for instance, by scrolling down.

  • The page is not self-contained and static anymore. The elements are created and modified dynamically (as result of execution of JavaScript code).

Approaches for Scraping data from Dynamic Websites

  • Reverse engineering JavaScript: sending AJAX requests manually (sometimes JS code can be machine-generated, e.g., Google Web Toolkit)
  • Rendering JavaScript

The latter workaround emulates the browser rendering that is parsing HTML, applying the CSS formatting and executing JavaScript to display a web page. In other words, we will simulate user actions.

Tools / requirements

  • Docker: an isolated collection of required libraries (and other dependencies) to run your application. It is like an artificial environment or a virtual machine on which we run Selenium.

  • Selenium: a framework that allows automating web-browser actions. Selenium controls actions of our headless browser.

  • (Headless) Chrome or Firefox: a web browser without a graphical user interface (GUI). Headless browsers provide automated control of a web page in an environment similar to popular web browsers, but are executed via a command-line interface or using network communication.

  • RSelenium: the package to control Selenium via R (rather than via command line).

  • R

Tools / requirements

Workflow

  1. Start Docker (open Docker app on macOS)

  2. Run Docker container of the selenium chrome browser

    docker run -d -p 4445:4444 selenium/standalone-chrome

    It is possbile to check oneself running docker ps that would yield the current running containers.

  3. Load the RSelenium package

    library(RSelenium)

  4. Connect to a running server

    remDr <- remoteDriver(remoteServerAddr = "localhost", port = 4445L,
                      browserName = "chrome")

Workflow

The last item generates a new object of the remoteDriver class. Objects of this class have dozens of methods that can be found by ?remoteDriver. We cover only the most used ones:

  • $open(): instantiates (open) the browser
  • $navigate(url): navigates the browser to a given url
  • $screenshot(display = TRUE): takes a screenshot of the current page
  • $findElement(): searches for an element on the page and returns it (class webElement)
    • $clickElement(): clicks the element
    • $sendKeysToElement(list(key = "end")): scrolls down
  • $getPageSource(): returns the current page source
  • $quit(): deletes the session & closes open browsers

Regular expressions (regex)

Introduction

A regular expression (regex for short) is a set of characters that specify a pattern.

Two types of regular expressions engines are used in R (difference in metacharacters):

  • POSIX extended regular expressions (actually, it is modified version of Ville Laurikari’s TRE engine, the default one)
  • Perl-like regular expressions

It is simple to search for a specific word or string of characters. Almost every editor on every computer system can do this. Regular expressions are more powerful and flexible:

  • words of a certain size
  • words with four or more vowels that end with an “s”
  • replace punctuation by underscore, etc.

Introduction

Tools

  • base R: grep, grepl, regexpr, gregexpr, sub, gsub, and strsplit. Not really intuitive names unless you are a hardcore Linux fan.

  • stringi package: build on top of icu4c C/C++ library, comprehensive and exhaustive set of functions and tools (244 functions)

  • stringr package: a stringi wrapper, a part of tidyverse, most commonly used 49 hand-picked functions with self-explanatory names that starts with str (i.e., str_length())

stringr

  • stringr convention of naming: functions start with str_ prefix
  • coherent order of arguments: easier to use in conjunction with lapply() and %>%
  • well-designed output of functions, e.g., the result of one function can be substituted as argument to the other

Installing and loading stringr:

install.packages("stringr")
library(stringr)

String basics

One can create strings with either single quotes ' or double quotes ". It is possible to use ' inside "", and vice versa:

"This is a string."
## [1] "This is a string."
"This is a string with '"
## [1] "This is a string with '"
'One more string, but this time with "'
## [1] "One more string, but this time with \""

Escape character \ (backslash)

From the last slide you probably spotted \ character in the last string before ". It is called an escape character. It allows specifying special characters or, in other words, “escaping”. E.g., specify " using double quotes "" and specify ' using sible quote '':

 "\"" # or '"'
## [1] "\""
'\'' # or "'"
## [1] "'"

Printed representation

Beware that the printed representation of a string is not the same as string itself, because the printed representation shows the escapes. To see the raw contents of the string, use writeLines() or cat():

x <- "\""
x # which is equialent to print(x) 
## [1] "\""
writeLines(x)
## "
cat(x)
## "

Other special characters

To use backslash, one specifies double backslash \\:

"\\"
## [1] "\\"

Common special characters:

"\n" # new line
"\t" # tab character

Unicode character with given hex code:

"\u{00B5}"
## [1] "µ"

Useful functions from stringr

  • str_length(): equivalent of nchar() and not length()

    str_length(c("aaa", "bbbbb", "zz"))
    ## [1] 3 5 2

  • str_c(): equivalent of paste()

    str_c(c("a", "b"), "c", sep = ", ", collapse = "")
    ## [1] "a, cb, c"

  • str_sub(): equivalent of substr()

    str_sub(c("some", "characters"), 1, 3)
    ## [1] "som" "cha"

Matching patterns with regular expressions

Again, regex is a language in its own right created to match patterns in strings.

We first learn how to compose regexes, that is how to describe the pattern. We use the function str_view(string, pattern) to highlight the pattern in strings in Viewer. The function str_view() highlights only the first match, while str_view_all() highlights all of them.

There is also a nice RStudio Addin for regex with interactive interface. To install it use:

devtools::install_github("gadenbuie/regexplain")

Basic matches

x <- c("black", "blue", "brown")
str_view(x, "bla")

Basic matches: metacharacter .

The metacharacter . matches any characters except a new line:

str_view(c("black", "blue", "brown"), "bl.")

Basic matches: metacharacter .

To match literal . in the string. One need to use an “escape” symbol \ (the same as in strings) to tell the regular expression you want to match it exactly, not use its special behavior. Regexes are represented by strings, for which \ is also the escape symbol. Therefore, to create the regular expression \. we need the string "\\.".

writeLines("\\.")
## \.
str_view(c("abc", "a.c", "bef"), "a\\.c")

Basic matches

Further, if you want to match a literal \, one needs to escape it by creating regex \\. Each of the \ in the regex should represented by two \ in the string, and therefore, to match one backslash \ we need to use "\\\\".

x <- "a\\b"
writeLines(x)
## a\b
str_view(x, "\\\\")

Anchors ⚓

By default, regular expressions will match any part of a string. It is possible to match the pattern at the start or at the end of the string by using anchors:

Anchors ⚓

  • ^ means the start of the string

    str_view(c("shirt", "hoodie", "t-shirt"), "^sh")

  • $ means the end of the string

    str_view(c("shirt", "hoodie", "t-shirt"), "rt$")

Character classes

The metacatacter . matches any character (except a new line). What about, for example, only digits or alphabetic characters? There are a number of predefined classes in R. For example:

  • digits \d (do not forget to “escape”) or [[:digit:]]

    str_view_all(c("132blabla", "hop 43"), "\\d")

  • punctuation characters [[:punct:]]

    str_view_all(c("33", "hop.43!"), "[[:punct:]]")

Character classes

  • upper-case letters

    str_view_all(c("This is", "a sentence YEAH"), "[[:upper:]]")

Please see a comprehensive list in the regex cheat sheet (see in references).

Character classes

One can also specify a list of characters that should be matched between [ and ]:

str_view(c("rmd", "rwd", "r.d", "rkc"), "r[mw]d")

Further, it is possible to match “anything except” by using ^:

str_view_all("aerg12wegcwef34._ ", "[^13_]")

Character classes

Metacharacters inside character classes (i.e., between [ and ]) have literal meaning:

str_view(c("a.c", "abc", "a.k"), "a[.].")

This can be used as an alternative to the backslash escaping symbol: it works for $, ., |, ?, *, +, (, ), [, and {, but not for ], \, ^, and -.

Alternation

str_view(c("grey", "gray"), "gr(e|a)y")
str_view(c("color", "colour"), "col(o|)r")

Repetition

To control the number of repetitions of the match, the following metacaracters are used:

  • ?: zero or one times

    str_view_all("I scream aaaaa and aaa", "aa?")

  • +: one or more times

    str_view_all("I scream aaaaa and aaa", "aa+")

  • *: zero or more times

    str_view_all("I scream aaaaa and aaa", "aa*")

Repetition

Specify the exact number of matches:

  • {n}: exactly n times
  • {n,}: n times or more
  • {,m}: at most m times
  • {n,m}: between n and m times
str_view_all("AA BB A BBBB AAAAA BB AAA BBBBB AA AAAAAAA", "A{4,5}")

Grouping and backreferences

You can refer to the same text as previously matched by a capturing group with backreferences, like \1, \2 etc. For example, the following regular expression finds all fruits that have a repeated pair of letters.

str_view(fruit, "(..)\\1", match = TRUE)

Tools

Various functions from stringr allows us to:

  • Determine whether strings contain a pattern
  • Find the positions of matches
  • Extract the content of matches
  • Replace matches with new values
  • Split a string based on a match

stringr::str_detect() and stringr::str_count()

bands <- c("Green Day", "The Offspring", "Blink-182", "Sum 41")
str_detect(bands, "\\d")
## [1] FALSE FALSE  TRUE  TRUE
str_count(bands, "\\d")
## [1] 0 0 3 2

stringr::str_extract()

price_sentences <- c("This one contains price of 324.21 and 4.25.",
                     "The price of the pizza is 25.1",
                     "The Moretti beer costs around 7 francs.")
str_extract(price_sentences, "(\\d{1,}\\.\\d{1,}|\\d{1,})")
## [1] "324.21" "25.1"   "7"
str_extract_all(price_sentences, "(\\d{1,}\\.\\d{1,}|\\d{1,})")
## [[1]]
## [1] "324.21" "4.25"  
## 
## [[2]]
## [1] "25.1"
## 
## [[3]]
## [1] "7"

stringr::str_replace()

messy_strings <- c("\n CHF 23 \n", "\n CHF 14 \n", "\n CHF 67 \n")
str_replace_all(messy_strings, "(\\s|CHF)", "")
## [1] "23" "14" "67"

stringr::str_split()

seventies <- "Led Zeppelin|Deep Purple|Black Sabbath"
str_split(seventies, "\\|")
## [[1]]
## [1] "Led Zeppelin"  "Deep Purple"   "Black Sabbath"
fruits_sentence <- "apples, pears, and bananas"
str_split(fruits_sentence, "(, and |, )")
## [[1]]
## [1] "apples"  "pears"   "bananas"
